04796nam a22007695i 9780801460975DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979968138  a97808014609757 a10.7591/97808014609752doi  a(DE-B1597)478290  a(OCoLC)763161321  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBH301.M54bR635 2016 7aART0151002bisacsh04a111.852231 aRoberts, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Total Work of Art in European Modernism /cDavid Roberts. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Artwork of the Future -- tPart II. The Spiritual in Art -- tPart III. The Sublime in Politics -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking book, David Roberts sets out to demonstrate the centrality of the total work of art to European modernism since the French Revolution. The total work of art is usually understood as the intention to reunite the arts into the one integrated whole, but it is also tied from the beginning to the desire to recover and renew the public function of art. The synthesis of the arts in the service of social and cultural regeneration was a particularly German dream, which made Wagner and Nietzsche the other center of aesthetic modernism alongside Baudelaire and Mallarmé.The history and theory of the total work of art pose a whole series of questions not only to aesthetic modernism and its utopias but also to the whole epoch from the French Revolution to the totalitarian revolutions of the twentieth century. The total work of art indicates the need to revisit key assumptions of modernism, such as the foregrounding of the autonomy and separation of the arts at the expense of the countertendencies to the reunion of the arts, and cuts across the neat equation of avant-gardism with progress and deconstructs the familiar left-right divide between revolution and reaction, the modern and the antimodern. Situated at the interface between art, religion, and politics, the total work of art invites us to rethink the relationship between art and religion and art and politics in European modernism.In a major departure from the existing literature David Roberts argues for twin lineages of the total work, a French revolutionary and a German aesthetic, which interrelate across the whole epoch of European modernism, culminating in the aesthetic and political radicalism of the avant-garde movements in response to the crisis of autonomous art and the accelerating political crisis of European societies from the 1890s forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArts, Europeany19th centuryxPhilosophy. 0aArts, Europeany20th centuryxPhilosophy. 0aArts, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aModernism (Aesthetics). 4aArt History. 4aGerman Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801460975zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801460975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801460975.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12S